                <note type="updated" update="general" import="tengyur-data-4020-4085_PH_new_v2.4.xml" date-time="2022-01-28T10:32:05.149Z" user="admin">In another major treatise, the Prajñāparamitopadeśa, Ratnākaraśānti also discusses the connection between the Vijnanavada/Cittamatra and the Madhyamaka.
            Beside the Laṅkāvatāra-sūtra he quotes in particular Nāgārjuna's Yuktiśāṣṭika in support of the doctrine of consciousness only (fol. 161b—162a; cf. 169 b 8). And he concludes
            that—notwithstanding any other differences—the Yogācārins and the Mādhyamikas finally agree concerning the four above-mentioned yogabhumis (fol. 169 b). In addition, Ratnākaraśānti
            criticizes the doctrine of those philosophers, Mādhyamikas as well as Yogācārins, who hold that knowledge has an image (sākāra-jñana) (fol. 168 a4, 170a4).</note>
